(200, 1, '2015-03-04 09:57:51', '2015-03-04 09:57:51', '[vc_row][vc_column width="1/1"][vc_custom_heading text="So what is a first look and why should you consider it in your wedding day?" font_container="tag:h2|text_align:center" google_fonts="font_family:Open%20Sans%3A300%2C300italic%2Cregular%2Citalic%2C600%2C600italic%2C700%2C700italic%2C800%2C800italic|font_style:400%20italic%3A400%3Aitalic"][vc_column_text]The moment when the groom sees his bride for the first time on their wedding day is almost always an emotional one, full of surprised faces and plenty of hugs and happy tears. In Australia this is almost always at the beginning of the wedding ceremony. It is almost ironic that something so intimate is done in public, but that has been what tradition has dictated.\r\n\r\nA first look is when the wedding photographer organises for the bride and groom to meet prior to the wedding ceremony. As a bit of a traditionalist I was horrified when I first had this suggested to me. I always thought one of the most special moments on the wedding day was watching the grooms face when he first sees his bride walking down the aisle. What I had not considered was the lack of intimacy of the situation.\r\n\r\nA first look involves usually just the bride, groom and photographer/s. A private location is found where the groom with his back often turned waits in anticipation for his bride. His bride appears and surprises him gaining a natural flood of emotions that is then captured by the photographer. This becomes their special moment where they can enjoy each others company and reconnect before an often hectic event. During this period the photographer will take the opportunity to get a number of candid and more formal shots of just the bride and groom.\r\n\r\nI was interested when a bride I interviewed stated it was the best decision on her wedding day. Intrigued by this statement, I explored her reasons for choosing to do a first look. Her responses were surprising and quite heartwarming. I could see the practical reasons for a first look, but weddings are emotional events and her primary reason touched my heart and opened my mind.[/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text="Top 5 Reasons for a First Look" font_container="tag:h2|text_align:left" google_fonts="font_family:Open%20Sans%3A300%2C300italic%2Cregular%2Citalic%2C600%2C600italic%2C700%2C700italic%2C800%2C800italic|font_style:400%20italic%3A400%3Aitalic"][vc_column_text]\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The only intimate time to spend with your partner on your wedding day  This is the time for the bride and groom to connect prior to the ceremony. A time to stop and breathe. In the lead up to the wedding there is usually so many things to do and not enough time to do them. Stress levels often prevent the bridal couple from truly enjoying their wedding day. This period of time is therefore dedicated just to the two of them. Nobody else to try to look after, just time for them to reconnect before they need to share the rest of the day with their friends and family. The grooms looking at his bride, and the brides looking at her groom in his very special intimate moment. Rather than taking away from the walking down the aisle moment (or traditional first look) which is shared with the closest 100 or so friends and family, the first look adds to a special moment into the bride and groom''s day.</li>\r\n	<li>Allows time for the bride and groom to get comfortable with the photographer and also with having their photos taken  Erin, a recent bride that I interviewed stated her groom was more nervous about having his photo taken than of being married. I was shocked to hear that having ones photo taken could cause that amount of stress. Her now husband was so relieved after the first look because he was able to interact with the photographers and began to relax into the process of having your every movement captured.</li>\r\n	<li>More relaxed post ceremony  As a guest at Erins wedding I was amazed at how calm she looked. She was the most relaxed bride I have ever seen in my life. Whilst Erins personality certainly contributed she stated that it was due to having the first look that allowed her to slow down and enjoy her day. She reminded me of a wedding she had attended only weeks before her own where the photographer was desperately trying to fit the wedding photos in prior to the commencement of the reception dinner, adding to the overall stress of the day.</li>\r\n	<li>More time with your guests after the ceremony  Not only are bridal couples more relaxed having done the majority of the formal photos prior to the ceremony, it also allows them more time to spend with their guests after the wedding.</li>\r\n	<li>More wedding photos  Lastly the bridal couple is typically provided with more wedding photos to choose from if they do a first look. Due to the more relaxed environment and setting, usually the photographer can gain more candid and intimate moments between the bride and groom.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nAll those advantages made me allocate time in each of my wedding packages for couples to choose to have ''a first look''. The reasons on my part were simple. I am able to catch some lovely candid moments with the bridal couple and they were able to be more relaxed during the day adding to the overall experience of the day.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]', 'Top 5 Reasons to include a First Look in your wedding day', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'top-5-reasons-to-include-a-first-look-in-your-wedding-day', '', '', '2015-03-05 08:54:44', '2015-03-05 08:54:44', '', 0, 'http://localhost/samantha-ohlsen-photography/?p=200', 1, 'post', '', 0),
